	<text>
		<body>
				<p>To the President and Members</p>
				<p>of the <addressee>KKMI of Philadelphia</addressee>.</p>
				<p>Gentlemen&#58;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">It is&#44; as you all know&#44; a laudable feeling&#44;<lb/> to be in the possession of the good opinion of our<lb/> fellow&#45;beings&#59; how much more must this be the case<lb/> with a person who had held a public trust&#44; to be assured<lb/> that he has acted so as he elicit the approbation of his<lb/> constituents. It has now happened that up to this date<lb/> I have not been honored with a certificate from your<lb/> honorable body such as I think my long public service<lb/> merits&#59; I would therefore be indebted to you to obtain<lb/> at the earliest possible moment such an expression of your<lb/> kind opinion as I could exhibit to all the world as the<lb/> evidence that my long public service as the minister of your<lb/> Congregation have met with your approbation.</p>
			<p rend="indent(8)">Respectfully yours&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(9)"><persName role="author">Isaac Leeser</persName></p>
				<p><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> <date>March 29&#44; 5617</date></p>
		</body>
